label.value: decreased alpha,alpha-trehalase activity during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of alpha,alpha-trehalase activity is lower than normal during a cellular response to salt stress.

label.value: normal cellular trehalose level during cellular response to heat

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of trehalose measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to a heat stimulus.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which RNA splice site specificity differs from normal. For example, different exons may be included or excluded, or introns in which the normally recognized 3' splice site AG nucleotides are mutated may be spliced.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which RNA splicing is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). All RNA splicing may be normal, or one splicing of or more specific RNA molecules may be specifically assayed.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which small nuclear RNA (snRNA) splicing is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). All snRNA splicing may be normal, or one splicing of or more specific snRNA molecules may be specifically assayed.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of mRNA splicing via the spliceosome is increased.

label.value: septation following abnormal chromosome segregation, with binucleate and anucleate compartment formation during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: An inviable phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell undergoes septation despite abnormal chromosome segregation, producing inviable daughter cells, and in which the septum forms in a position that partitions both nuclei into one compartment, when the cell is subject to salt stress. Cell separation may or may not be completed.

definition.value: In cells with this phenotype, septation has proceeded despite chromosome segregation failing to complete normally. Chromosome segregation may be incomplete or entirely abolished. Consider also annotating to 'cut' (FYPO:0003155) or its descendants, because these phenotypes often co-occur.

label.value: fragmented nucleus during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleus is broken into multiple small fragments that are smaller than a normal nucleus, hen the cell is subject to salt stress.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of arsenate reductase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of arsenate reductase activity is decreased.

label.value: abolished protein phosphorylation during cellular response to arsenic-containing substance

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during a cellular response to an arsenic-containing substance such as arsenate.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects signal transduction. Signal transduction is the process in which a signal is conveyed to trigger a change in the activity or state of a cell. It begins with reception of a signal and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. regulation of transcription or regulation of a metabolic process. A phenotype may affect one or more steps in one or more signal transduction pathways.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: constitutively activated MAPK cascade involved in cell wall organization or biogenesis

value.value: A signal transduction phenotype in which the MAPK cascade involved in cell wall organization or biogenesis is activated continuously.
A phenotype in which one or more transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules contains no queuosine residues.

label.value: viable elongated vegetative cell, elongated upon mitotic entry

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is viable and elongated, and in which mitosis begins when the cell is longer than normal.
A cell phenotype in which a protein is localized to discrete regions in the cytoplasm, visible as foci or dots by microscopy, to a greater extent observed than in normal (wild type) cells.

definition.value: This term can be used for proteins that do not normally localize to discrete cytoplasmic regions, or for proteins that do normally show punctate localization but with such localization increased in a mutant. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased punctate nuclear protein localization during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that is normally localized to discrete regions in the nucleus, visible as foci or dots by microscopy, is abnormally localized such that fewer dots are observed than in normal (wild type) cells during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone does not occur. The mitotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the biosynthesis of DNA does not occur.

label.value: abolished protein localization to double-strand break site

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the region of a chromosome at which a DNA double-strand break has occurred is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal mitotic cell cycle regulation during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cellular response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the regulation of the mitotic cell cycle in response to ionizing radiation is abnormal. Normally, cell cycle progression is slowed or arrested transiently following exposure to ionizing radiation. The most common abnormality is for the cell cycle to progress as in the absence of ionizing radiation.

label.value: increased duration of mitotic DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the duration of cell cycle arrest or delay due to regulation by any mitotic DNA damage checkpoint is greater than in wild type during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: sensitive to UV during mitotic G1 phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to ultraviolet light during G1 phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of beta-glucanase, any enzyme that degrades cell wall polysaccharides by hydrolyzing beta-glucan linkages, than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of hypothemycin than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to L-azetidine-2-carboxylic acid. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of L-azetidine-2-carboxylic acid that allows wild type cells to grow.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of azetidine-2-carboxylic acid acetyltransferase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which azetidine-2-carboxylic acid acetyltransferase activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of azetidine-2-carboxylic acid acetyltransferase activity is increased.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the initiation of nuclear DNA replication begins earlier than normal.

label.value: increased rate of pre-replicative complex assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of pre-replicative complex assembly is increased.

label.value: viable branched, elongated, multiseptate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is viable, forms one or more branches near a septum, is elongated, and has more than one septum.

label.value: inviable aseptate mononucleate vegetative cell, normal cell length

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell is inviable, is normal length, and contains one nucleus and no septum.

label.value: abolished cell population growth on raffinose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which a cell population does not grow in a medium containing raffinose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Use this term for a population of cells that does not grow with raffinose as the carbon source, but does grow using a different carbon source (a cell population that does not grow on any media would be considered inviable). Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has a normal length.

label.value: increased protein level in plasma membrane

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in the plasma membrane is higher than normal when the cell is in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: An increased level of a protein in the plasma membrane may result from increased protein transport to the membrane ('increased protein localization to plasma membrane FYPO:0002127), decreased endocytosis from the membrane ('abolished endocytosis' FYPO:0000421 or 'decreased endocytosis' FYPO:0000422), or both. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which glutathione gamma-glutamylcysteinyltransferase activity is absent.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing copper ions.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing zinc ions.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing mercury ions.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing selenite ions.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing silver ions.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of L-ergothioneine measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of hercynine (N(alpha),N(alpha),N(alpha)-trimethyl-L-histidine) measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of hercynylcysteine sulfoxide measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of hercynylselenocysteine measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of L-selenoneine measured in a cell is too low to detect.

label.value: increased cellular L-ergothioneine level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-ergothioneine measured in a cell is higher than normal.

label.value: increased cellular L-selenoneine level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-selenoneine measured in a cell is higher than normal.

label.value: increased cellular hercynine level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of hercynine (N(alpha),N(alpha),N(alpha)-trimethyl-L-histidine) measured in a cell is higher than normal.
